    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Peace Overtures in Colombia'' (editorial, May 2):</p>
        <p>It is apparent that the fortitude and good will of Colombia's president, Andres Pastrana, is the only beacon of hope left for the Colombian people since this beautiful, self-sufficient country is now on the brink of economic and social chaos.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Peace Overtures in Colombia'' (editorial, May 2):</p>
        <p>It is apparent that the fortitude and good will of Colombia's president, Andres Pastrana, is the only beacon of hope left for the Colombian people since this beautiful, self-sufficient country is now on the brink of economic and social chaos.</p>
        <p>The guerrillas have superior weaponry and cannot be toppled by the Colombian military. There is nothing left for the Colombian government except peace negotiations.</p>
        <p>The government has failed its law-abiding citizens who are growing weary of the continued violence. It is understandable why so many of them have taken up arms against the guerrillas. Anarchy and lawlessness have endured for too long. The peace effort has been a Sisyphean one. Mr. Pastrana deserves an olive branch.</p>
        <p>RICARDO BRITTON  Arlington, Tex., May 3, 2000</p>
      </block>
